Brenda's is a gem in the middle of a pretty rough neighborhood. First bit of advice, take a Lyft directly there, don't walk. Now that we have the safety warning aside, the food and atmosphere are amazing. They had a wonderful three piece band playing, we are talking upright bass, accordion and guitar. The French music was flowing as well as some good libations from the bar. As for the food, I recommend it all but their crawfish beignets are legendary. They are a must try.

We had a 30 min wait Friday at 11am (which I incorrectly thought would be the slowest time). The shrimp & grits was amazing, the muffuletta and side of BFC thigh were very good and the gumbo was good. Service was good and the food came out very fast.

My first time here I was not impressed. Nothing was memorable or blew me away. Grits were so bland!! Beignets were decent; crawfish beignet won points over the others. But an hour+ wait for this?! However... second chance. Wowzers! Total different story! * BFC * the spices and batter on the fried chicken was delicious! Crispy and full of flavor! Chicken was juicy inside, nicely seasoned collard greens had big chunks of ham hock, and the biscuit was crumbly. ** GARLIC SHRIMP GRATIN ** It has all the components comparable to the best make-up/ drunk/ angry/ passionate sex you could possibly have - a guilty indulgence of a steamy, drippy, hot mess with a funky flavor you can't quite put your finger on. It's like a bad boy you can't stay away from.. So bad for you but so good you can't stop!! I had to know what ingredients were in there. Our waitress told us: Goat cheese, shrimp, with a mystery sauce: mixture of shrimp, garlic, parmesan, picquillo peppers, and a whole lot of mouth-watering inducers. F.. I could use some right about now. Warning.. there is a layer of orangey oil, but just move that aside and get to the goods! The space is narrow and small. Write your name on the chalk board, wait to seated, and be prepared to cozy up to your neighbors. The tables are that tiny. The long line is a hit or miss. First time I waited over an hour, second time we were seated immediately. But now that I know they serve sex in a bowl, I'd gladly wait. Besides, the longer the wait, the sweeter the nectar and the more explosive when you finally get into that honey.

Summary: Balanced fried chicken was crispy on the outside, and very moist and juicy inside, but flavoring was a bit on the balanced side. 3.5/5 Went here for lunch last Friday. The wait for 2 was 15 minutes, so not bad at all. I was looking forward to the chicken, since I had heard all the hype for quite a while now. I ordered the BFC, my wife got the gumbo. Maybe my expectations were too high... The fried chicken was above average. The good: incredibly crunchy skin, and not too oily too, which seems paradoxical but great; and very juicy and moist meat (white meat). I believe I had a drumstick and thigh. The bad: for cajun/soul food, it was kinda bland. I prefer my fried chicken salty, and the more paprika/cayenne, the better for me. I tasted the buttermilk, but to me, it was just lacking that unhealthy saltiness that fried chicken needs. I lathered it with hot sauce. On the other hand, my wife's gumbo was delicious! Rich enough, and texture was not overly thick. Loved the roux in their gumbo. And the flavors, oh my! Bold, a little spicy and delicious! The biscuit was also fantastic, crispy on the outside and very fluffy inside. Based on the fried chicken, this place gets 3.5 from me, but depending how you like your fried chicken, you might give it a 4.

This uber-popular restaurant was a bookmark that we finally got to enjoy on our recent visit. With over 5,000 Yelp reviews, believe the hype. My boyfriend and I came for breakfast with a pal just this past Saturday and it was worth the wait. Opened in 2007 by Chef Brenda Buenviaje, she of Creole and Filipino descent from New Orleans, the lady cooks up the French-influenced soul food that you want in your belly. Notorious for long lines, we had no problem on Saturday morning at 9:00am. They will not seat you unless your whole party is present. After 9:30am, there were people waiting to be seated, but it wasn't crazy yet; if you wait until 10:00am and beyond, though, it could be a while. Having studied the menu for months, I already knew what I wanted before we got here, but there are daily specials, too. BEIGNET FLIGHT: You can choose four and we opted for one of each kind: crawfish, chocolate, Granny apple, and plain. The crawfish and chocolate were my favorites. The three of us cut each one into thirds and shared. So delicious and highly recommended! SHRIMP AND GRITS: The shrimp were large and tender, the grits were creamy, the dish was everything I was hoping for! I ordered a biscuit on the side, as well, but it wasn't really necessary because I was a little full from the beignets. I ended up giving one whole shrimp to the boyfriend which tells you how full I really was. I'm not going to reinvent the wheel with this review, but that was my experience and I look forward to coming back again and again. PS: Two doors down is Libby Jane Café, named after Chef Brenda's wife and business partner. Stop in there if you're waiting for a table at this restaurant and/or for some nice coffee and dessert. It's all in the family! #400 :)

    Summary: Balanced fried chicken was crispy on the outside, and very moist and juicy inside, but flavoring was a bit on the balanced side. 3.5/5

    Went here for lunch last Friday. The wait for 2 was 15 minutes, so not bad at all. I was looking forward to the chicken, since I had heard all the hype for quite a while now.
    I ordered the BFC, my wife got the gumbo. Maybe my expectations were too high...

    The fried chicken was above average. The good: incredibly crunchy skin, and not too oily too, which seems paradoxical but great; and very juicy and moist meat (white meat). I believe I had a drumstick and thigh.

    The bad: for cajun/soul food, it was kinda bland. I prefer my fried chicken salty, and the more paprika/cayenne, the better for me. I tasted the buttermilk, but to me, it was just lacking that unhealthy saltiness that fried chicken needs. I lathered it with hot sauce.

    On the other hand, my wife's gumbo was delicious! Rich enough, and texture was not overly thick. Loved the roux in their gumbo. And the flavors, oh my! Bold, a little spicy and delicious!

    The biscuit was also fantastic, crispy on the outside and very fluffy inside.

    Based on the fried chicken, this place gets 3.5 from me, but depending how you like your fried chicken, you might give it a 4.

     Having studied the menu for months, I already knew what I wanted before we got here, but there are daily specials, too.
     BEIGNET FLIGHT: You can choose four and we opted for one of each kind: crawfish, chocolate, Granny apple, and plain. The crawfish and chocolate were my favorites.  The three of us cut each one into thirds and shared.  So delicious and highly recommended!
    SHRIMP AND GRITS:  The shrimp were large and tender, the grits were creamy, the dish was everything I was hoping for!  I ordered a biscuit on the side, as well, but it wasn't really necessary because I was a little full from the beignets.  I ended up giving one whole shrimp to the boyfriend which tells you how full I really was.

    I'm not going to reinvent the wheel with this review, but that was my experience and I look forward to coming back again and again.  
    PS:  Two doors down is Libby Jane Café, named after Chef Brenda's wife and business partner.  Stop in there if you're waiting for a table at this restaurant and/or for some nice coffee and dessert.  It's all in the family!
     #400 :)

Like I said, I really wanted to love it here.... But when the crawfish beignets came out (we got excited and ordered three - not three beignets, three orders of three beignets each order), I was ready to dive in. I cut them in half and the crawfish beignet looked so promising, yet unfortunately lacked in flavor. I didn't see the hype. I wish we ordered only 1... We also ordered po boys (catfish and oyster) and the BFC (Brenda's fried chicken). Po boys were okay, nothing spectacular - too much bread. The BFC was the best part of the meal. I honestly think I just come to the hyped places expecting too much because this has happened to me too many times on vacation trying out the hyped spots but to be honest, this is my true opinion on my experience alone.
